11/16/21, 15:29 - <sukriti><guin/>: #include<stdio.h>
#include<stdlib.h>
#include<stdbool.h>

void input(int row, int col, int matrix[][col]){
	for(int i=0; i<row; i++){
		for(int j=0; j<col; j++){
			scanf("%d",&matrix[i][j]);
		}
	}
}
void display(int row, int col, int matrix[][col]){
	for(int i=0; i<row; i++){
		for(int j=0; j<col; j++){
			printf("%d ",matrix[i][j]);
		}
		printf("\n");
	}
	printf("\n");
}

bool isParseMatrix(int row, int col, int matrix[][col]){
    int size = 0;
    for(int i=0; i<row; i++){
        for(int j=0; j<col; j++){
            if(matrix[i][j]==0)
                size++;
        }
    }
    if(size>(row*col)/2)
        return true;
    else
        return false;
}
void addMatrix(int row, int col,int matrix1[][col],int matrix2[][col],int summatrix[][col]){
    for(int i=0; i<row; i++){
        for(int j=0; j<col; j++){
            summatrix[i][j] = matrix1[i][j]+matrix2[i][j];
        }
    }
}

int main(){
    int row1, row2, col1, col2;
	printf("Enter the number of rows of 1st matrix : ");scanf("%d",&row1);
	printf("Enter the number of columns of 1st matrix : ");scanf("%d",&col1);
	printf("Enter the number of rows of 2nd matrix : ");scanf("%d",&row2);
	printf("Enter the number of columns of 2nd matrix : ");scanf("%d",&col2);
	int matrix1[row1][col1],matrix2[row2][col2];
	printf("Enter the matrix 1 elements : \n");input(row1,col1,matrix1);
	printf("Enter the matrix 2 elements : \n");input(row2,col2,matrix2);
	int summatrix[row1][col1];
	if(!isParseMatrix(row1,col1,matrix1) && !isParseMatrix(row2,col2,matrix2))
		printf("Not parse matrix");
	else{
		if(row1 != row2 || col1 != col2)
			printf("Add of these two parse matrix is not possible\n");
		else{
			summatrix[row1][col1];
			printf("Summation of two parse matrix is : \n");
			addMatrix(row1,col1,matrix1,matrix2,summatrix);
			display(row1,col1,summatrix);
		}
	}
	// printf("Summation matrix is : ");
	// display(row1,col1,summatrix);

	return 0;
}

*A week-long FREE workshop that gets you interview-ready. Cover the basics, work on projects, evaluate your preparation and get tips to better your CV! Give yourself a chance to receive 360 learning before you sit for your next interview.*


Session 01: Day 1

Master the Basics of DSA
Practice Coding Questions
Attempt the Assessment Tests
Preparation for Interviews
Session 02: Day 2

Overview of OOPS & OOAD
Case Study regarding the same
Real-world problems and projects
Develop scalable and extensible MVP (Minimum Viable Product)
Session 03: Day 3

Tips on Resume Building
OS / DBMS / CN top most asked questions
Relevance of these topics in the GATE exam
Session 04: Day 4

System Design Interview Preparation
Overview about System Design
Kind of questions asked in interviews
Optimized approach to solve questions
One case study to explain key concepts like scalability, throughput, or data sharding
Session 05: Day 5

Recently Asked Interview Questions
Session 06: Day 6

Most Asked Interview Questions
Session 07: Day 7

Tc=1/fc;
Lc=100*Tc
Ec=2;
tc=0:.001*Lc:Lc;
c=cos(2*pi*fc*tc);
%plot(tc,c)
%normalized message signal
fm=2000;
Tm=1/fm;
Lm=10*Tm;
ts=.001*Lm;
fs=1/ts;
tm=0:ts:Lm;
M_t=cos(2*pi*fm*tm);
%plot(tm,M_t)
m(1)=0 
a=[]
for i=1:1:10
    x=m(i);
    e=Ec+x.*M_t;
    AM=e.*c
    a=[a;AM]
    m(i+1)=m(i)+0.1
end
s1=a(1,:)
s2=a(5,:)
s3=a(10,:)
subplot(3,1,1)
plot(tm,s1)
subplot(3,1,2)
plot(tm,s2)
subplot(3,1,3)
plot(tm,s3)

5/18/22, 18:20 - Gouranga (ECE) NSEC: My Dear Students
*Coursera has stopped offering free courses from 29/03/2022.* 
Now, you enroll (directly) a course from Coursera / Udemy without invitation email and apply for FREE through Financial Aid link

*Steps for https://www.coursera.org :*
Visit (i) coursera.org, (ii) search your desired course (iii) go to course page (iv) if you find a sentence "Financial aid available" then you may get this course as free of cost (v) enroll that course using a new email address / account (vi) again apply for "Financial Aid" after login and enrolment.
You may visit a 3rd party website to know the technique to get a free course from Coursera - https://skillscouter.com/free-coursera-courses/

*Steps for Udemy.com:*
Now most of the short duration courses are available free of cost from Udemy.com
Visit https://www.udemy.com/courses/free/ and search your desired course and enroll that course with a new email address.
You may visit a 3rd party website which suggest how to get a course as a free of cost from Udemy - https://udemyfreecourses.org/
*Remember, a eight (8) hours duration course will give you one (1) credit point*

Thank you and best wishes for learning MOOCs for your Honours Degree

For any doubts you may WhatsApp (preferable) or call me
Regards
PSP Sir

5/20/22, 12:38 - +91 93341 93063: format short;
clear all;
clc;
info=[2 3 1;1 2 3;3 1 2];
b=[9;6;8];
a=[info b];
for i=1:size(a,1)
    for j=i+1:size(a,1)
        key1=a(j,i)./a(i,i);
        a(j,:)=a(j,:)-key1.*a(i,:);
    end
end
x=zeros(1,size(info,2));   %creating a 1 row 4 column matrix having 00
for i=size(a,1):-1:1
    out=sum(a(i,i+1:end-1).*x(i+1:end));
    x(i)=(a(i,end)-out)./a(i,i);
end
fprintf('ansr is %f',x);

6/15/22, 23:58 - Ankit (ECE) NSEC: am = input('am =');
fm = input('fm =');
ac= input('ac=');
fc= input('fc=');
m = am/ac;
t= 0 :pi/1000:2*pi; 


subplot (3,1,1)
plot(t,am.*cos(fm*t));
grid on


subplot(3,1,2)
xlabel("time")
plot(t, ac.*cos(fc*t));
title("c(t)")
grid on


subplot(3,1,3) 
xlabel("time")
x= ac*(1+m.*cos(fm*t)).*cos(fc*t);
plot(t, x);
title("AM SGNAL")
grid on

L=length(x)
Fs=10*fc;
NFFT = 2^nextpow2(L)
pxx = fft(x,NFFT);
f = Fs/2*linspace(0,1,NFFT/2+1)
spec=2*abs(pxx(1:NFFT/8+1));
figure()
plot(f(1:NFFT/8+1),pow2db(spec));
%power calculation

fprintf("m= %d\n", m);
ma=m*m;
fprintf("m^2= %d\n",m*m);
sbp= (ac*ac*ma)/8;
dsb= sbp*2;
fprintf("sideband power of a single band = %d Wattand that of double side band is %d \n", sbp, dsb)
pc= (ac*ac)/2;
fprintf("cariier power =%d watt \n", pc);
am_power= pc*(1+ma/2);
fprintf("am_power= %d watt", am_power);
p_carrier=max(abs(pc))
p_carrier_dB=pow2db(pc)
p_sideband=max(abs(sbp))
p_sideband_dB=pow2db(sbp)
6/15/22, 23:58 - Ankit (ECE) NSEC: clc
fc=6000;
Tc=1/fc;
Lc=100*Tc
Ec=2;
tc=0:.001*Lc:Lc;
c=cos(2*pi*fc*tc);
%plot(tc,c)
%normalized message signal
fm=2000;
Tm=1/fm;
Lm=10*Tm;
ts=.001*Lm;
fs=1/ts;
tm=0:ts:Lm;
M_t=cos(2*pi*fm*tm);
%plot(tm,M_t)
m(1)=0 
a=[]
for i=1:1:10
    x=m(i);
    e=Ec+x.*M_t;
    AM=e.*c
    a=[a;AM]
    m(i+1)=m(i)+0.1
end
s1=a(1,:)
s2=a(5,:)
s3=a(10,:)
subplot(3,1,1)
plot(tm,s1)
subplot(3,1,2)
plot(tm,s2)
subplot(3,1,3)
plot(tm,s3)

6/16/22, 12:49 - Aritra Bera (ECE) NSEC: am = input('am =');
fm = input('fm =');
ac= input('ac=');
fc= input('fc=');
m = am/ac;
t= 0 :pi/1000:2*pi; 


subplot (3,1,1)
plot(t,am.*cos(fm*t));
grid on


subplot(3,1,2)
xlabel("time")
plot(t, ac.*cos(fc*t));
title("c(t)")
grid on


subplot(3,1,3) 
xlabel("time")
x= ac*(1+m.*cos(fm*t)).*cos(fc*t);
plot(t, x);
title("AM SGNAL")
grid on

L=length(x)
Fs=10*fc;
NFFT = 2^nextpow2(L)
pxx = fft(x,NFFT);
f = Fs/2*linspace(0,1,NFFT/2+1)
spec=2*abs(pxx(1:NFFT/8+1));
figure()
plot(f(1:NFFT/8+1),pow2db(spec));
%power calculation

fprintf("m= %d\n", m);
ma=m*m;
fprintf("m^2= %d\n",m*m);
sbp= (ac*ac*ma)/8;
dsb= sbp*2;
fprintf("sideband power of a single band = %d Wattand that of double side band is %d \n", sbp, dsb)
pc= (ac*ac)/2;
fprintf("cariier power =%d watt \n", pc);
am_power= pc*(1+ma/2);
fprintf("am_power= %d watt", am_power);
p_carrier=max(abs(pc))
p_carrier_dB=pow2db(pc)
p_sideband=max(abs(sbp))
p_sideband_dB=pow2db(sbp)

fc=6000;
Tc=1/fc;
Lc=100*Tc
Ec=2;
tc=0:.001*Lc:Lc;
c=cos(2*pi*fc*tc);
%plot(tc,c)
%normalized message signal
fm=2000;
Tm=1/fm;
Lm=10*Tm;
ts=.001*Lm;
fs=1/ts;
tm=0:ts:Lm;
M_t=cos(2*pi*fm*tm);
%plot(tm,M_t)
m(1)=0 
a=[]
for i=1:1:10
    x=m(i);
    e=Ec+x.*M_t;
    AM=e.*c
    a=[a;AM]
    m(i+1)=m(i)+0.1
end
s1=a(1,:)
s2=a(5,:)
s3=a(10,:)
subplot(3,1,1)
plot(tm,s1)
subplot(3,1,2)
plot(tm,s2)
subplot(3,1,3)
plot(tm,s3)
6/16/22, 12:49 - Aritra Bera (ECE) NSEC: clc
clear all;
close all;

fc = 5000;
Tc = 1/fc;    %Time period = 0.00016
Lc = 100 * Tc;    %0.016
tc = 0:0.001*Lc:Lc;
c = cos(2*pi*fc*tc);
%plot(tc,c);

fm = 2000;
Tm = 1/fm;    %0.0005
Lm = 10 * Tm;
%ts = 0.001*Lm;
%fs = 1/ts;
tm = 0:0.001*Lm:Lm;
M_t = cos(2*pi*fm*tm);
%plot(tm,M_t)

Ec = 2;
m(1) = 0
a = []
for i=1:1:10
    x = m(i);   %x = 0 0.1
    e = Ec+x.*M_t;    %e = 1+x.[M_t] e=[1 1 1 1.....1]
    AM = e.*c;    % Am = [1 0.8 ......]
    a = [a;AM];   % a = [ ; 1 0.8.....]   (Ec + x.M_t) * c
    m(i+1) = m(i) + 0.1;
end

s1 = a(1,:);
s2 = a(5,:);
s3 = a(10,:);
subplot(3,1,1)
plot(tm,s1)
subplot(3,1,2)
plot(tm,M_t)
subplot(3,1,3)
plot(tm,s3)

8/23/22, 16:36 - Tathagata Sau (ECE) NSEC: Ans. Of Cyber law
8/23/22, 16:36 - Tathagata Sau (ECE) NSEC: How Digital Signature is used for Authentication of Electronic Document? Digital Signature: Digital Signature is a number which is created using private key of a key pair (combination of private and public key). A user who wants to send a legal valid electronic document should have a key pair. The public key is used for verification and it distributed to agencies like Income Tax Dept, Registrar of Companies etc while private key is for the user himself for creating digital signature.

For any legal valid electronic document, two requirements are there: â€¢ Integrity of document i.e. document has not changed once created

âš« Authentication i.e. document is signed by authorized user.

These requirements are satisfied with the following techniques:

âš« Hash Function or known as Hashing is used for integrity of document

âš« Digital Signature used for Authentication of documents.

The following steps are part of creating a legal valid electronic document/message:

(1) Sender creates the electronic document/message (2) Sender executes Hash Function on electronic document and this provides a message digest (i.e. it provides a big number which will change if document's content changes)

(3) This message digest or number is encrypted by using private key and this encrypted number is

known as Digital Signature

(4) Sender sends the electronic document and Digital Signature to receiver (5) Receiver uses the Sender's certified public key and decrypts the Digital Signature and generates the message digest or a number

(6) Receiver executes the Hash Function on received electronic documents and generates a message digest.

Mesmerizer is the annual cultural fest of NSEC that aims to celebrate and showcase the diverse cultural talents of students from different colleges. This year, the fest will be held in two phases. 

In the first phase ( *14th and 15th January* ), we will be having the inter college competitions in areas such as music, dance debate, art, and more in the college campus. In the 2nd phase ( *19th January* ), we will have the prize distribution ceremony followed by the guest performance at *Northern Park, Bhawanipur.*ğŸ“
